\begin_body

\begin_layout Abstract
The main issue of DFSA anti-collision algorithms is to increase the reading
 efficiency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
-------------------------------------------------
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
xxx:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
 The conventional definition of DFSA reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DFSA_shoute_Random"

\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta=\frac{number\, of\, successful\, slots\,(a_{1})}{Frame\, length\,(L)}\label{eq:eff basic equ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main goal of FSA algorithm is to find the optimal value of the frame
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 which maximizes the reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, based on the equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: number of slot definition"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eff basic equ"

\end_inset

.This result in the equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta=\frac{n}{L}\left(1-\frac{1}{L}\right)^{n-1}\label{eq:eff calss f(L)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eff calss f(L)"

\end_inset

, the reading efficiency 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is maximized when 
\begin_inset Formula $L=n$
\end_inset

 as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DFSA_shoute_Random"

\end_inset

.
 However in practical applications, the number of tags in the interrogation
 region is unknown and even it is known in some cases, the tags move which
 make the exact current number of tags varies and unknown.
 To achieve maximum throughput, the anti-collision protocol should first
 estimate the current number of tags in the interrogation region, then set
 a dynamic value of the frame length based on the number estimated number
 of tags.
 That protocol is called Dynamic Frame Slotted ALOHA (DFSA) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DFSA_shoute_Random"

\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Anti-collision-process-with"

\end_inset

 presents an example for DFSA anti-collision process.
 We assumed the number of tags at the interrogation area is four tags with
 frame length equal to four.
 According to the figure, the first reading cycle the first slot is idle,
 a collision occurred at the second slot between 
\begin_inset Formula $tag_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $tag_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $tag_{3}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $tag_{4}$
\end_inset

 are identified in slots 3,4 respectively.
 so we have only two tags to be identified in the next reading cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $tag_{1}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $tag_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 So to maximize the reading efficiency, the frame size should be equal to
 the number of tags in the interrogation region, therefore the frame size
 in the second reading cycle will be equal 2.
 It is clear that is the robustness of the estimation method is the most
 important part of the anti collision protocol, because if the anti-collision
 protocol has a big estimation error, the frame length will be set to a
 wrong value, which means that this protocol will work with a low reading
 efficiency.
 However the anti-collision protocols which have an accurate tag estimation
 method, will work always almost with the maximum reading efficiency.
\end_layout

